  • scientists & “clearing houses” typically use standardized textual representations (Cohen, 1988)

  • Translations of ES (e.g.Â months of learning) often carry undesired characteristics (Baird & Pane, 2019; Kim et al., 2022; Lortie-Forgues et al., 2021)


  • Alternative: visualizations (Franconeri et al., 2021)
  • How do we normally communicate ES? As scientists & some clearing houses use standardized and textual representations
  • there is compelling evidence that textual representations of standardized ES are challenging for teachersâ perception and understanding
    • CohenâS d / Percentile gain = rated as little informative
    • depending on which metric we present: perceived treatment effectiveness differ
  • Some clearing houses use Translations of ES (e.g.Â months of learning) often carry undesired characteristics
    • although they are often perceived as more informative (Lortie-forgues)

  • Alternative: visualizations

Background & Focus

What we know about visualizing data (for lay people)

accurately estimating statistical information: plot type plays a role

  • box plots: spread; distribution
  • bar/line plot: mean
  • modified stock chart: maxima, minima; spread (Albers et al., 2014; Pierce & Chick, 2013)
  • there is a lot of basic research on visualizing statistical information
  • however, when plotting ES a lot of these phenomena we know about on a small scale come together and interact
  • there is first evidence that the type of visualization we choose
  • plays a role as to how accurately lay people estimate statistical information

Background & Focus

What we know about visualizing data (for lay people)

accurately estimating statistical information: plot type plays a role

  • box plots: spread; distribution
  • bar/line plot: mean
  • modified stock chart: maxima, minima; spread (Albers et al., 2014; Pierce & Chick, 2013)



supporting the process: enrichment options

  • benchmarks (anchoring) (Cohen, 1988; Jacowitz & Kahneman, 1995)
  • cues (signaling) (Schneider et al., 2018)
  • Enrichment options for these visualizations may further support the complex processes of sense-making
  • A common approach is to provide standardized benchmarks against which also researchers typically anchor their interpretations
  • research on multimedia learning suggests that the use of cues (e.g.Â arrows, labels) can direct observersâ attention.
  • This so-called signaling effect can increase understanding and reduce cognitive load

Background & Focus

What we know about visualizing data (for lay people)

  • Laypeople are unimpressed by plotted ES (McPhetres & Pennycook, 2020)


  • adding means to plots increases perception of ES (Kale et al., 2020)
  • for d=.9: ~55% would say “Group A definitively has higher scores than Group B”
    • they would call it something between “small” and “medium”
  • in a sense that it increases bias

Methods

Delphi Study

  • 4 Experts in Data Visualization, 4 Experts in Science Communication
  • Phase 1: Collecting 16 plot types
    (for group scores on a metric variable)
  • now if we want to find out what are promising plot types to communicate ES
    we face the challenge that there is a universe of potential plot types to investigate
  • so in a pilot study we consulted experts in Data Visualization and Science Communication to help us collect and rank
  • “plot types that they gauge suitable for depicting effect sizes to teachers”
  • synthesizing these lists, resulted in 16 suitable plot types

Delphi Study

  • 4 Experts in Data Visualization, 4 Experts in Science Communication
  • Phase 1: Collecting 16 plot types
    (for group scores on a metric variable)
  • Phase 2: Rating and Ranking of 44 plots

(7-point Likert scale; totally random - totally accurate)

Background & Focus

What we know about visualizing data (in general)

  • there is quite some basic research on visualizing information
  • for example using position (dot plot) it is easier estimating the mean than using areas
  • these results give us first ideas of what to expect
  • however, when plotting ES, several of these phenomena come together: most plots use position AND length AND area
